Not really buying the 'quick counts'. Right now 1.1m/7.3m votes are counted and Mesa is leading 43.8% to Arce's 35.2%

Putting 100 into Arce because I had earlier assumed Mesa would win (and apparently these preliminary results have enough weight that the current president is congratulating Arce), but I have to say I am very doubtful about these exit polls/quick counts. They are totally inconsistent with all opinion polling of recent months and it would seem they are also inconsistent with the official count as it now stands.

Calling it for Mesa, most likely in Round 1. Arce has significantly underperformed just about everywhere except with Bolivians abroad. Chuquisaca with 10% in now and massive underperformance by MAS is sustained. Barring some enormous change, this thing is a foregone conclusion.

Vote counting will take several days, but comparing results with 2019, I would definitely want to be Mesa right now. For example, Chuquisaca province, his party won by only 2 points in 2019. Right now he's up by 55!
Compared with 2019, initial CC results looking good and MAS not so good. Bumping this up again. Still a little uncertainty. Official count here: https://computo.oep.org.bo
Initial results looking favorable for Mesa, compared with Evo Morales results.
Two realistic candidates remain, Mesa is up a little in 2 recent polls, Arce is up big in 2 others. Difficult to name a clear frontrunner, but I give Arce the edge here.

Candidacy of María Bayá, of the conservative Nationalist Democratic Action Party, is withdrawn on eve of election. Another 50-100 basis points of the electorate is now going to the anti-MAS vote. Bumping up odds of Carlos Mesa accordingly.
For a win in the first round, a candidate needs to get more than 40% of the vote and 10% more than the opponent with the 2nd most votes [1,2].
Small insanity to pick political winners in a place you've never even visited. I'll go sit on the fence for the rest of the week.

Jorge Quiroga has dropped out. Though he was polling at only about 2%, these will all go to the anti-MAS vote, making it that much more likely that Arce doesn't win the 1st round. Bumping up Mesa's odds. https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6964600/bolivian-ex-leader-out-of-president-vote/?cs=14232

Bumping this one up based on further learning about the parties and candidates. It's MAS vs. an array of anti-MAS candidates. The only way Arce is winning this is if he gets +10 in Round 1. No polling is showing that, and no movement in the polling is showing that. If no winner in Round 1, this thing is 90% Mesa. https://www.as-coa.org/articles/explainer-presidential-candidates-bolivias-2020-special-elections

- I believe the chance of the elections happening in 2020 to be around 95% now - I adjusted my probabilities after seeing recent polls which indicate a tight race between Arce and Mesa well ahead of Anez. The president is elected in a two-round election. If Arce does not get a majority in the first round (or 40% of the votes with >10% difference to Mesa), there will be a run-off election between Arce and Mesa. Quite a lot of uncertainty then comes from the question whether Anez and Camacho join forces with Mesa.

Bolivia's legislature has approved the use of a "toxic bleach" as a remedy for Covid-19. Link https://www.businessinsider.com/bolivian-lower-house-approves-toxic-bleach-as-covid-19-treatment-2020-8 The statements being made by MAS leader and ex-president Morales, exiled in Argentina, can be seen as actually mobilizing opposition to his movement, and "his" candidate Arce, who really does not have exposure as a leader or influencer in Bolivia MSM nor on the nation's "low-fi" social media. Clearly, Anez recognizing Guaido as president in VEN has earned her a modicum of support from Washington minions who want the former busdriver who seems to be still running VEN, thrown under the bus. Considering how the "half moon" group of states Santa Cruz, Beni, Pando and Tarija, oppose the "centralization" that Arce will try to continue if he wins, and that Santa Cruz state alone, is the major economic powerhouse in Bolivia, Anez, who was a senator from "Half Moon" state Beni for a decade, might surprise... with a little help from her friends, the godfearing among them.

While I still believe that the plurinational state of Bolivia is not an exception in South America with regards to SARS-CoV-2 and the public health situation will deteriorate much faster than the current numbers suggest (any pathway between Chile and Argentina is possible), and I assume Bolivia is even less prepared to secure a fair and legal election process with a large share of mail-in ballots than the US, I prefer some re-adjustments for tactical reasons. An election in October 2020 can of course be pushed through, but with likely fatal consequences in the aftermath and a high price in terms of death toll.

New election date is in October, which could be feasible, though there is still a chance it will be pushed back again. However, given the protests accompanying this delay, it is unlikely to be delayed without a large uptick in COVID cases directly before the election date. Currently cases are on the rise, with over 1,700 reported yesterday. If this continues, they may have no choice but to delay again, but the government has plenty of time and incentive to address the current conditions and hold the elections in October. With little chance of a run-off given current polls, there is a good chance someone will be elected in 2020.

There were 124 new cases on May 3rd (when the election was originally supposed to be held). There were over 2,000 cases on August 1st (yesterday). If levels were considered too risky back then, it is likely that the election day will again be pushed back, probably by several months given the current trends in Bolivia. That, when combined with the possibility of a second wave still in the air, means it is becoming less and less likely the election will be held in 2020, especially since it is seen as a "special election", meaning there isn't much precedent for when you can and cannot push it back. With Anez so far down in polls, this becomes even more likely, even if not for corrupt reasons, just for the public good. She gains nothing from holding the elections this year during the pandemic, so as we approach the new election date, I suspect another postponement. The rest simply reflects current polling.

Decreasing the probability for Áñez, in favor of Mesa, as the polls are showing likely her coming up third. Ncreasing Mesa’s probability by as much.

Polls show Arce at ~30%, Mesa at 20%, Áñez at ~17%. This leads me to these scenarios: 1. Runoff elections between Arce and Áñez with Áñez enjoying support by Mesa. This would lead to Áñez win most likely. 2. Runoff elections between Arce and Mesa with Mesa enjoying support by Áñez. This would lead to Mesa win most likely. Equally likely to the 1 above. 3. Runoff election between Arce and either Mesa or Áñez with Arce still consolidating at above 50%. I believe this to be less likely than the above, as there is a center right momentum in Latin America currently with Brazil etc so I think Bolivia is following the same trajectory. I give Arce majority about 30% max probability. I will split the rest between a Mesa and Áñez, with more to Mesa.

First, the main issue is whether election will be held in 2020. Recently, it has been postponed for the second time to Oct 2020. It is forecast that pandemic will reach its peak in September 2020. The scheduled election in Oct is dependent on the curve of the pandemic. As of this moment, the chances are that election will not be postponed third time. Second issue is whether Arce has any chances of being disqualified. It depends on the court ruling, however, the allegation of electoral violation over a statement may not be strong enough. Hence, in the event, if Arce is not disqualified, he has the backing of the voters with highest rating among the presidential candidates. Hence, the forecast depends on the pandemic and court ruling, which will become clearer in the following weeks.

I started fresh, took the crowd out of consideration, built up a reasonable distribution of probabilities (subjectively but sincerely) and then trimmed back uniformly to total 100%. That said, the crowd seemed pretty spot on with the information available to us. Áñez and "Someone Else" seemingly have no chance (read: *legitimate* chance,) but oh well, benefit of the doubt here. As far as what will happen with C19, I think it is safe to expect an election will be held considering the current local trajectory. If anything, perhaps turnout will take the biggest hit. Or maybe it'll drive turnout. If the health ministry says the risk is too high, I believe the election can be postponed until Jan 2021.

Mesa is ‘Yesterday’s Man’ with a failure to previously govern.
